package enclavid:host@0.1.0;

/// Value shapes carried by the host capabilities in this package. Kept
/// in a SEPARATE types interface (WASI-style types-vs-behaviour split)
/// so the value type can be `use`d without importing the capability
/// getter, and so `enclavid:host` stays a self-contained leaf package.
///
/// The three embedded refs (`localized-ref` / `icon-ref` /
/// `disclosure-field-ref`) are RESOURCES, minted only by the host's
/// `embedded-{i18n,icons,disclosure-fields}` capabilities. A component
/// cannot construct one — the handle IS the proof the key was declared,
/// so membership needs no crypto token. They live HERE (a shared
/// interface) rather than inside each embedded interface so the strict
/// per-component routing twin — a structural clone of `embedded-i18n` /
/// `embedded-icons` with a distinct id — still references the SAME
/// resource type and subtype-matches the component's canonical import.
///
/// `blob` is likewise a host-owned resource — one stored byte-blob, minted
/// by the runtime into `event::media` and rehydrated across rounds via its
/// `constructor(blob-hash)`. It is the UNIVERSAL unit: a captured camera frame
/// is a blob, a future uploaded document / PDF is a blob — the host stores and
/// hands them out identically. It lives here (not in
/// `enclavid:shared-types/capture`) so both the policy and any verification
/// plugin reference the SAME resource type and can pass a handle across the
/// fused policy↔plugin boundary; the bytes stay host-side and enter a
/// component's linear memory only when it pulls `bytes`. `blob-hash` is the
/// content address that identifies any stored blob. The `clip` record that groups
/// the blobs of one capture is NOT here — it's policy-facing (only
/// `media-result` uses it) and lives in `enclavid:policy/types`; this package
/// holds only what the host mints or owns.
interface types {
    /// One static configuration value the consumer supplies at session
    /// creation (was `eval-args`). Read on demand via
    /// `session-context.props`.
    variant prop {
        %string(string),
        int(s64),
        float(f64),
        %bool(bool),
        null,
    }

    /// A validated reference to a `localized` catalog entry — surfaces as
    /// UI text once the host resolves it to the applicant's locale.
    resource localized-ref;
    /// A validated reference to an `icons` catalog entry — surfaces as a
    /// machine icon name the applicant frontend dispatches.
    resource icon-ref;
    /// A validated reference to a `disclosure-fields` catalog entry —
    /// surfaces as the machine `display-field.key` the consumer receives.
    resource disclosure-field-ref;

    /// A blob's content ADDRESS — the hex-encoded 32-byte BLAKE3 of its bytes.
    /// An opaque STRING token (NOT one of the `-ref` resources above — those are
    /// opaque per-round capability handles; this is a serializable value): the
    /// policy stashes it in its opaque sealed `state` and passes it to the `blob`
    /// constructor to rehydrate across rounds; it never inspects it. A string
    /// (not raw bytes) for cross-language ergonomics — JS/Go/Rust: JSON-safe,
    /// `==`-comparable, map-keyable, loggable (`[]byte` can't even be a Go map
    /// key). TYPE-AGNOSTIC: a future `document`/`pdf` resource reuses the same
    /// store and hash. (Algo-agility, if ever needed, via a multihash-style
    /// `algo:` prefix inside the string.)
    type blob-hash = string;

    /// One stored byte-blob — a host-owned lazy CONTENT handle (has `bytes`),
    /// distinct from the opaque `-ref` capability handles above. The universal
    /// unit of storage: 1 blob ↔ 1 `blob-hash` ↔ 1 sealed blob host-side. A
    /// captured camera frame is a blob; a future uploaded document / PDF is a
    /// blob too. The semantic KIND lives in the record that groups blobs
    /// (`clip.frames`) and the plugin that reads them — not in this type. A
    /// verification plugin pulls the bytes via `bytes` (so they enter linear
    /// memory only at use); the policy keeps the `blob-hash` in `state` to
    /// rehydrate the blob in a later round. For camera frames: pristine bytes,
    /// no container, no inter-frame compression that could mask the forensic
    /// signal.
    resource blob {
        /// Rehydrate the blob with this content hash from the session's media
        /// store. Own-session only (cross-session is cryptographically blocked).
        /// Returns a COLD handle — no host IO yet; the bytes are pulled lazily on
        /// the first `bytes()`. TRAPS on a miss (unknown / wrong-length hash): a
        /// fabricated hash is never a legitimate outcome for a correct policy (it
        /// only ever stashes hashes it got from a real `hash()`), so it fails loud
        /// rather than handing the policy a recoverable branch. (A constructor is
        /// possible precisely because there's no error result — only blob-or-trap.)
        constructor(hash: blob-hash);
        /// Pull this blob's bytes into the caller's linear memory. For a
        /// rehydrated (constructed) blob this is the LAZY load point. Bounded by
        /// the component's memory limit.
        bytes: func() -> list<u8>;
        /// This blob's content hash — stash in `state` to rehydrate the blob in
        /// a later round via the constructor.
        hash: func() -> blob-hash;
    }
}
